 {"id":"asupersync-l6l","title":"Implement lab runtime with virtual time and deterministic scheduling","description":"# Lab Runtime with Virtual Time and Deterministic Scheduling

## Purpose
The lab runtime is the executable semantics of Asupersync:
- **virtual time** (discrete ticks)
- **deterministic scheduling** (seeded, reproducible)
- **trace capture + replay**

This is what makes concurrency bugs reproducible artifacts instead of “heisenbugs”.

## Key Guarantees
Given the same lab config (including seed) and the same user program:
- the runtime produces the same observable trace
- replay can reproduce a failing run

## Core Constraints
- Avoid ambient globals.
- Avoid OS entropy / wall-clock time for scheduling decisions.
- Prefer minimal dependencies; implement deterministic PRNG internally (see bead: deterministic PRNG utility).

## LabRuntime Structure

```rust
pub struct LabRuntime {
    state: RuntimeState,
    virtual_time: Time,

    /// Deterministic PRNG for tie-breaking (no rand crate).
    rng: DetRng,

    trace: TraceBuffer,
    config: LabConfig,
}

pub struct LabConfig {
    pub seed: u64,
    pub max_time: Option<Time>,
    pub max_steps: Option<u64>,

    /// Lab-only strictness knobs.
    pub panic_on_leak: bool,
    pub panic_on_invariant_violation: bool,
}
```

## Virtual Time
Time advances only when no runnable tasks exist.

Algorithm:
1. If scheduler has runnable tasks: do not advance time.
2. Otherwise, jump to next timer deadline (if any).
3. Wake any tasks whose timers expire.
4. Check deadline expiries and request cancellation as needed.
5. Emit `TraceEvent::Tick`.

This yields the “sleeps are instant in wall-clock time” property while preserving a meaningful virtual timeline.

## Deterministic Scheduling
When multiple tasks are eligible to run, break ties deterministically using `DetRng` seeded by `LabConfig.seed`.

Important: determinism requires that tie-breaking inputs are stable.
- do not iterate hashmaps/sets and rely on their order
- prefer ordered iteration or explicit sorting by IDs

## Main Loop (Sketch)

```rust
loop {
    if should_stop_by_limits(config, virtual_time, steps) {
        break;
    }

    if let Some(task_id) = scheduler.pick_next(virtual_time, &mut rng, &state) {
        poll_task(task_id);
        steps += 1;
        verify_invariants_if_enabled();
    } else {
        tick_virtual_time();
    }
}
```

## Trace Capture
Every semantic operation emits a trace event. The trace model should stay small and semantic:
- spawn/complete
- cancel/propagate
- reserve/commit/abort/leak
- finalize/close
- tick

The trace is the primary debugging artifact for test failures.

## Replay
Replay means: “run again under the same seed/config and ensure we reproduce the same trace”.

Minimum viable replay:
- re-run the scenario under the same seed
- compare traces
- report first divergence with context

(Phase 5 adds canonicalization and equivalence-class reasoning; Phase 0 replay can be strict byte-for-byte equality.)

## Acceptance Criteria
1. Same seed/config yields identical traces for the same program.
2. Virtual time advances only when nothing runnable exists.
3. Trace capture is complete enough for invariants/oracles.
4. Replay reports divergence precisely.

## Testing Requirements
- Determinism oracle runs at least 3 scenarios twice and asserts trace equality.
- Deadlock/idle detection is explicit and traceable.

